# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-s-morse
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The **1866 great fire of Portland** was a large fire that spread throughout the city of Portland, Maine, on July 4, 1866—the second Independence Day after the end of the American Civil War.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire burned out the morning of July 5; while over a thousand buildings were destroyed, there were few fatalities.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Occurring five years before the Great Chicago Fire, it was the greatest fire yet seen in an American city.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire started in a boat house near today's Hobson's Wharf on Commercial Street, likely caused by a firecracker or a cigar ash.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire spread to a lumber yard and on to a sugar house, then spread across the city, eventually burning out early the next morning on Munjoy Hill in the city's east end.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Four people died in the fire and 10,000 people were made homeless.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Around 1,800 buildings (1,200 homes) were burned to the ground, including the first of three city halls which have stood at the present Congress Street location.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Also lost was the federal Exchange Building, which was replaced with the custom house.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Soon after the fire, Portland native and acclaimed poet Henry Wadsworth Longfellow described his old home town: "Desolation, desolation, desolation.
[src:edward-s-morse/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] It reminded me of Pompeii, that 'sepult city.'" More than 600 buildings were constructed in the four months following the fire.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The **Great Kantō Earthquake** (Japanese: 関東大地震, *Kantō daijishin*, or 関東大震災, *Kantō daishinsai*) was a megathrust earthquake that struck the Kantō Plain on the main Japanese island of Honshu at 11:58:32 JST (02:58:32 UTC) on Saturday, 1 September 1923.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] It had an approximate magnitude of 8.0 on the moment magnitude scale (Mw), with its epicenter located some 100 km (62 mi) southwest of the capital Tokyo.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake devastated Tokyo, the port city of Yokohama, and the surrounding prefectures of Kanagawa, Chiba, and Shizuoka, causing widespread damage throughout the Kantō region.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The event was a complex disaster, with modern research indicating it consisted of three consecutive shocks in the span of several minutes.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The initial megathrust event in Kanagawa Prefecture was followed three minutes later by a magnitude 7.2 earthquake centered beneath Tokyo Bay, and two minutes after that by a magnitude 7.3 shock in Yamanashi Prefecture.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fires, exacerbated by strong winds from a nearby typhoon, spread rapidly through the densely populated urban areas, accounting for the majority of the devastation and casualties.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The death toll is estimated to have been between 105,000 and 140,000 people, including tens of thousands who went missing and were presumed dead.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over half of Tokyo and nearly all of Yokohama were destroyed, leaving approximately 2.5 million people homeless.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster triggered widespread social unrest, including the Kantō Massacre, in which ethnic Koreans and others mistaken for them were murdered by vigilante groups based on false rumors.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In the aftermath, the Japanese government declared martial law and undertook extensive relief and restoration efforts.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake prompted ambitious plans for the reconstruction of Tokyo, aiming to create a modern, resilient imperial capital under the leadership of Home Minister Gotō Shinpei.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, these plans were often met with political contestation, financial constraints, and local resistance, leading to a reconstruction that, while significantly improving infrastructure, fell short of the grandest visions.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also fueled debates about national identity, modernity, and societal values, with many commentators interpreting the event as a divine punishment for perceived moral decline and advocating for spiritual and social regeneration.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake remains a pivotal event in modern Japanese history, profoundly impacting urban planning, disaster preparedness, and social consciousness.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] 1 September is commemorated annually in Japan as Disaster Prevention Day.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Kantō region of eastern Japan is prone to major earthquakes due to its location near complex tectonic plate boundaries.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The 1923 earthquake occurred when the Philippine Sea Plate subducted beneath the Okhotsk Plate (sometimes considered part of the North American Plate) along the Sagami Trough.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The initial shock, occurring at 11:58:32 JST on 1 September 1923, was a complex event.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Modern analysis indicates a dual rupture on a broad trench-type fault: the first rupture occurred near Odawara in Kanagawa Prefecture, some 100 km (62 mi) southwest of Tokyo, followed about ten seconds later by a second shock on the other side of Sagami Bay near the Miura Peninsula.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This was followed minutes later by two major aftershocks: a magnitude 7.2 earthquake beneath northern Tokyo Bay at 12:01, and a magnitude 7.3 earthquake in Yamanashi Prefecture at 12:03.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor accounts consistently describe these three distinct seismic events.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake immediately toppled structures, crushed people, and caused widespread panic.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor accounts describe an initial period of stunned silence followed by a frantic rush as people tried to reunite with family and salvage belongings.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Engineer Mononobe Nagao recalled the earth shaking "back and forth for what seemed like 15 seconds", followed by violent vertical convulsions that knocked people to the ground.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Writer Tanaka Kōtarō described the sound as akin to a giant "blackening whirlwind" churning up the earth from "deep underground".
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Within thirty minutes of the first tremor, more than 130 major fires broke out across Tokyo, particularly in the densely populated eastern and northeastern sections.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These fires were fueled by overturned charcoal braziers used for midday meals, leaking gas from ruptured lines, and flammable debris from collapsed wooden buildings.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Strong winds, associated with a typhoon passing off the coast, fanned the flames, creating massive firestorms that swept through the city.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The air temperature in some areas reached 46 °C (115 °F).
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The combination of ongoing aftershocks and rapidly spreading fires led to pandemonium.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Millions of residents attempted to flee, often carrying their possessions, which clogged the already damaged streets and bridges.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Kawatake Shigetoshi described being trapped in a "wave of people" in eastern Tokyo, unable to move as fires approached from multiple directions.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many sought refuge in open spaces, such as parks and the grounds surrounding the Imperial Palace, but these areas quickly became overcrowded.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Waterways like the Sumida River also became congested with boats as people tried to escape by water, only to face sparks and burning debris falling from the sky.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster quickly overwhelmed Tokyo's infrastructure and its capacity for an orderly evacuation.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake was one of the most destructive natural disasters of the 20th century.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly half of Tokyo and virtually all of Yokohama were transformed into "blackened, corpse-strewn wastelands".
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake and subsequent fires destroyed an estimated 397,119 homes in Tokyo Prefecture alone, leaving about 1.38 million people homeless in Tokyo City.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Across the seven affected prefectures (Tokyo, Kanagawa, Chiba, Saitama, Shizuoka, Yamanashi, and Ibaraki), a total of 2.5 million people were displaced.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In addition to buildings, the earthquake buckled roads, collapsed bridges (362 destroyed and 70 heavily damaged in Tokyo), twisted train tracks, snapped water and sewer pipes, and severed telegraph lines.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Tokyo's main aqueduct from Wadabori collapsed in two places and required extensive repairs.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The sea floor in Sagami Bay dropped by over 400 meters (1,300 ft) at the epicenter, triggering tsunamis that inundated low-lying coastal communities.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fires were the primary cause of destruction, accounting for 90 percent of the fatalities.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In Tokyo, districts like Asakusa, Kanda, Nihonbashi, Kyōbashi, Honjo, and Fukagawa were largely incinerated.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Honjo Clothing Depot, a large open area where tens of thousands sought refuge, became a death trap when a massive firestorm (a *tatsumaki* or whirlwind of fire) engulfed it, killing an estimated 40,000 people in minutes.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor Koizumi Tomi described the site as "hell on earth", surrounded by "endless rows of bodies: red, inflamed bodies; black, swollen bodies; bodies partially buried under ash and smoldering remains".
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The government administration was crippled.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In Tokyo, 44 percent of the main buildings burned to the ground, including the police headquarters and the ministries of Home Affairs, Finance, Education, Communications, and Railways.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The vast majority of police stations and municipal and ward offices crumbled or burned.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Out of Tokyo's 196 primary schools, 117 were destroyed, along with numerous higher girls' schools, trade schools, colleges, and universities.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Social welfare facilities, including public dining halls, cheap lodging homes, and crèches, were annihilated.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over 160 public and private hospitals in Tokyo were destroyed.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster exacerbated the economic downturn of the early 1920s and contributed to a genuine banking crisis in 1927.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly 7,000 factories were destroyed, including major spinning, dyeing, and tool manufacturing plants.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Financial institutions suffered heavily, with 121 of 138 bank head offices and 222 of 310 branch offices in Tokyo City consumed by fire or reduced to rubble.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Insurance policies offered little relief, as most contained clauses exempting companies from earthquake-related damage; eventually, the government intervened to facilitate partial payouts.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Reconstruction brought a new surge of imports and, under these combined pressures, an early return to the gold standard was impossible.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also led to significant unemployment.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In September 1923, the unemployment rate in the wards of Tokyo reached 45% (59% for men, 28% for women).
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 15 November, across Tokyo Prefecture, 178,887 people were registered as unemployed, with the commerce and industry sectors most affected.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The human toll of the Great Kantō Earthquake was catastrophic.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Early estimates put the death toll as high as 140,000, but modern research based on the *1923 Great Kantō Earthquake Disaster Report* puts the total number of fatalities at 105,385.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Of these, 91,781 deaths (87%) were attributed to fires, while 11,086 (10.5%) were due to being crushed by collapsing buildings.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Other causes included drowning and landslides.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Kanagawa Prefecture suffered 32,838 deaths, while Tokyo Prefecture had 70,387.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An additional 13,275 people remained classified as missing twelve months after the earthquake.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] People died in numerous ways: crushed by collapsing buildings, trampled in panicked crowds, burned alive in the fires, or drowned in rivers and canals while attempting to escape the flames.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some victims suffocated as fires consumed oxygen, while others were boiled alive in ponds offering no protection from the intense heat.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The smell of burning human flesh and decaying bodies permeated the air for weeks.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Disposing of the dead became a major public health concern, leading to mass cremations, particularly at the Honjo Clothing Depot.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In the immediate aftermath of the earthquake, law and order broke down in many parts of the affected region.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This period was characterized by the spread of rumors, the formation of vigilante groups (*jikeidan*), and the massacre of ethnic Koreans and others mistaken for them, as well as the murder of political activists by the authorities.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Widespread destruction of communication infrastructure contributed to an atmosphere of uncertainty and fear.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Rumors spread rapidly, often relayed by refugees fleeing the disaster zone.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some stories suggested that Mount Fuji had erupted or that a large tsunami had washed away Yokohama.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most damaging rumors, however, concerned alleged activities by Koreans.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Originating from looting by Japanese in Yokohama that was misattributed to Koreans, false reports circulated that Koreans were poisoning wells, committing arson, looting, and organizing attacks on Japanese.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These rumors were given a degree of legitimacy when some government officials, including Gotō Fumio of the Home Ministry, broadcast messages warning of "organized groups of Korean extremists" attempting to "commit acts of sedition".
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] On 2 September, the police headquarters, lacking manpower to confirm eyewitness reports, passed them on as factual and issued a statement that "unscrupulous Koreans are committing acts of arson and other forms of violence".
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fueled by these rumors and a climate of fear and xenophobia, Japanese vigilante groups, known as *jikeidan*, formed across the Kantō region.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By mid-September, an estimated 3,689 such groups were operating, ostensibly to prevent fires, stop looting, and maintain order.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, many of these groups, often armed with makeshift weapons like clubs, swords, and bamboo spears, targeted Koreans and, in some cases, Chinese, Okinawans, and Japanese from certain regions who were mistaken for Koreans due to their accents.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Estimates of the death toll in what became known as the Kantō Massacre vary significantly.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Police confirmed the deaths of 248 Koreans, while an investigation by the Governor-General of Korea determined 832 had been killed or were missing.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A separate investigation by Korean students concluded that 2,613 Koreans had been killed; some modern estimates reach as high as 6,000.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Victims were often subjected to brutal violence, including beatings, stabbings, and lynchings, sometimes after being "tested" for their Korean identity (e.g., by being asked to pronounce Japanese words that were difficult for Koreans).
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While some police and military personnel attempted to protect Koreans, others were complicit in the violence or turned a blind eye.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Although police made belated corrections to the rumors on 3 and 4 September, few perpetrators were prosecuted; of 125 vigilante group members tried, only 32 received formal sentences, and 91 received suspended sentences.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Contemporary commentators like Hoashi Ri'ichirō and Oku Hidesaburō condemned the massacres as "extremely disgusting and internationally shameful" and a "disgraceful act that exposed a moral flaw".
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The chaos also provided a cover for the murder of political dissidents.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most prominent case was the Amakasu Incident, in which the anarchist Sakae Ōsugi, his partner Noe Itō, and his six-year-old nephew were arrested and then brutally killed by a squad of military police led by Lieutenant Masahiko Amakasu.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake struck at a time of political uncertainty in Japan.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Prime Minister Katō Tomosaburō had died on 24 August, and Admiral Yamamoto Gonnohyōe, selected to form a new cabinet, had not yet succeeded when the disaster occurred.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also forced the postponement of Crown Prince Hirohito's marriage and accession ceremonies.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This elite-level political vacuum contributed to confusion over who had the authority to deploy police and military personnel.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] General Ishimitsu Maomi, deputy commander of the Imperial Guard Forces, acted first, deploying troops to protect imperial locations.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Akaike Atsushi, inspector general of the Tokyo Metropolitan Police, faced an overwhelming task with outnumbered and unprepared forces.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The new cabinet was formally appointed on the afternoon of 2 September, sworn in on the lawn of the Akasaka Detached Palace amid falling ash, as other ministerial buildings were deemed unsafe.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] One of the first decisions of the new cabinet was to declare martial law over what remained of the capital on 2 September.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This ushered in the largest peacetime domestic mobilization and deployment of the army in Japan's pre–World War II history, with eventually over 52,000 troops deployed to Tokyo and Yokohama.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The martial law headquarters was granted extensive powers, including administering relief and public safety, prosecuting lawbreakers, prohibiting public gatherings, censoring information, stopping and searching individuals, and entering private homes.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Martial law remained in effect until 15 November.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Initial military deployment was fraught with difficulties.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Commanders arriving in Tokyo found a near total absence of reliable information and lines of communication were non-existent.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The military had to rely on aerial reconnaissance and around 2,000 army-trained carrier pigeons for communication.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The zone of martial law was progressively expanded to cover all of Tokyo and Kanagawa Prefectures by 3 September, and Chiba and Saitama Prefectures by 4 September.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] To counter rumors and vigilante violence, particularly against Koreans, military authorities were empowered to arrest individuals, disband suspicious groups, and confiscate weapons.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] From 4 September, military and police began to collect and transport Koreans to government-run detention centers for "protective custody"; by the end of September, 23,715 Koreans had been taken into these centers.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Yamamoto cabinet created the Emergency Earthquake Relief Bureau (*Rinji shinsai kyūgo jimukyoku*) to oversee all relief and recovery efforts.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Providing emergency medical assistance was an immediate priority, but initial efforts were largely unsuccessful.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many organized rescue and first aid squads were unable to reach the worst-hit areas like Honjo, Asakusa, and Kanda until 4 or 5 September due to destroyed infrastructure and unofficial checkpoints by vigilante groups.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A dearth of medical supplies, due to the destruction of numerous hospitals and dispensaries, further hampered efforts.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Relief Bureau concentrated its limited medical resources at large open areas like Hibiya Park and Ueno Park, where tens of thousands of refugees had congregated.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over the longer term, mobile clinics and dispensaries proved most effective.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Relief Bureau created 41 units, and other organizations like Tokyo Prefecture, the Japan Red Cross Society, and the Mitsubishi Corporation also operated mobile clinics.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 30 November, these public and private clinics had provided care to 447,111 sufferers.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Temporary hospitals, some in tents donated by American and French governments, accommodated over 6,000 seriously wounded people.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Securing food and water was a critical challenge.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Mayor Hidejirō Nagata learned on 2 September that the army's main supply depot in Fukagawa, holding 8,000 *koku* of rice (enough to feed over 500,000 people for six days), had been completely destroyed by fire.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The military managed to amass over 120,000 combat rations and 60,000 rations of rice from other stores.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 4 September, military units were distributing dried noodles.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Eventually, 74,048 *koku* of rice were transported from military installations across Japan to distribution centers in Tokyo and Yokohama.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The government also appealed to prefectural governors for rice donations, receiving pledges of 61,490 *koku* in the first week.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An "Emergency Requisition Ordinance" allowed the government to requisition foodstuffs and other materials.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Transporting these supplies was a major logistical challenge due to damaged rail lines and docks.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Navy personnel spent a week repairing 86 piers at Shibaura and Ryōgoku, while army forces cleared railway lines and rebuilt track.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Conservative estimates suggest that 1.25 million people received rice distributions between 6 and 10 September.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Water supply was an even more significant problem.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Tokyo's main water plant was not heavily damaged, but pipes and aquifers were severed in over two hundred locations.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Warships tanked water from Yokosuka, Osaka, and Nagoya, and the army requisitioned water barrels to transport clean water.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By the end of December, nearly 40 million gallons (151 million liters) of drinking water had been transported.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Shelter options were bleak for Tokyo Prefecture's 1.55 million homeless.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Nearly 800,000 people left Tokyo or Yokohama, first on foot and later via restricted rail service (from 11 September), to stay with relatives or friends elsewhere.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] About 250,000 people dispersed to other parts of Japan, including 17,704 to Kobe, 7,600 to Hokkaidō, and some even to Japan's colonies like Taiwan and Karafuto.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Those remaining in Tokyo flooded large open spaces such as Hibiya Park, Ueno Park, and the Imperial Palace grounds.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] On 9 September, municipal authorities began constructing temporary barracks.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Meiji Shrine site housed nearly 6,000 refugees, Ueno Park over 9,500, and Hibiya Park 7,000.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many of these open spaces became shantytowns.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Barracks were often cramped, with an average of 0.6 *tsubo* (about 2 square meters (22 sq ft)) of floor space per person.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Sanitation was a major problem, with makeshift latrines overflowing.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While a modest number of refugees left barrack housing by the end of 1923, many more returned to the disaster zone and erected private makeshift shacks.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By October 1923, 539,450 people were living in 111,791 such temporary abodes.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Government officials and media outlets made concerted efforts to construct the Great Kantō Earthquake as an unprecedented national calamity, requiring a unified national response.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Newspapers, the chief medium for disseminating news, played a lead role.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Major papers like the *Tokyo Nichi Nichi Shinbun*, *Osaka Asahi Shinbun*, and *Osaka Mainichi Shinbun* used emotive headlines, harrowing survivor accounts, vivid photographs, and even documentary motion pictures to convey the disaster's horror and scale to a national audience.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These portrayals often framed the disaster in terms of wartime analogies, emphasizing themes of sacrifice and national unity.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The forty-ninth-day memorial service held on 19 October 1923, at the site of the Honjo Clothing Depot, attended by over 200,000 people and leading politicians, was a meticulously choreographed event.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Speeches by figures like Gizō Kasuya and Shōzaburō Horie explicitly linked the victims' sacrifices to the future reconstruction of Tokyo and Japan, urging national unity and effort.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Visual culture, including lithographic prints and postcards, also played a significant role in disseminating the image of a devastated but resilient capital, and of a concerned government responding to the crisis.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Postcards depicting dead bodies, while sometimes classified as contraband, were widespread and brought the human cost of the disaster to a national audience in a stark manner.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A widespread interpretation, embraced by numerous elites across various sectors of society, was that the earthquake was an act of divine punishment (*tenken* or *tenbatsu*) or heavenly warning.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This view was not confined to religious leaders but was articulated by bureaucrats, politicians, academics, and social commentators.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster was seen as a response to Japan's perceived moral decline, materialism, luxury-mindedness, hedonism, and excessive individualism that had become prominent since World War I.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The entertainment districts of Tokyo, such as Asakusa, and centers of consumer spending, like the Ginza, were often singled out as epicenters of this perceived degeneracy and thus seen as specifically targeted by the heavens.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The destruction of icons of modern consumerism, such as the Mitsukoshi Department Store and the twelve-story Ryōunkaku tower in Asakusa, was imbued with symbolic meaning.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This interpretation served as a cosmological bolster for critiques of contemporary society and legitimated calls for social, moral, and ideological reform.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake was thus framed as a moral wake-up call, placing Japan at a crossroads between decline and renovation.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The interpretation of the earthquake as divine admonishment fueled calls for national spiritual renewal (*seishin fukkō*) and economic moderation.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An Imperial Rescript Regarding the Invigoration of the National Spirit, issued on 10 November 1923, became a foundational document for this movement.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] It urged Japanese people to reject frivolousness, extravagance, and extreme tendencies, and to embrace simplicity, sincerity, fortitude, diligence, thrift, moderation, loyalty, and filial piety.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Government campaigns, such as the 1924 Campaign for the Encouragement of Diligence and Thrift (*Kinken shōrei undō*), employed the memory of the earthquake to promote austerity and national savings.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Policies like the 1924 luxury tariff, which placed a 100 percent duty on a wide range of imported goods deemed luxuries, aimed to curb consumer spending and foster economic self-discipline.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While these measures had mixed results in altering consumer behavior in the long term, they reflected a broader elite concern with reorienting Japanese society towards more traditional and disciplined values.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The push for spiritual renewal also involved using schools, neighborhood associations, and new media like film and radio to inculcate desired moral values.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The devastation of Tokyo unleashed a wave of optimism among many bureaucrats, urban planners, and social reformers, who saw an unparalleled opportunity to rebuild the city as a modern, rational, and resilient metropolis.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Figures like Gotō Shinpei, Abe Isoo, and Fukuda Tokuzō argued that "old Tokyo" had been a breeding ground for social ills due to overcrowding, poor sanitation, poverty, and inadequate infrastructure.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake, they believed, created a chance to rectify these problems and construct a capital that would reflect new social values and assist the state in managing its subjects.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disorientation and destruction offered a "free field" for new ideas, but reconstruction under Gotō's direction was swift.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many visions for the new Tokyo were influenced by "authoritarian high modernism," emphasizing state-led planning, technical and scientific progress, and intervention in many aspects of human life, from public health and housing to urban layout and transportation.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Plans called for wider, paved streets, extensive green belts and parks, modern public housing, new sanitation systems, and improved transportation networks.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some, like Gotō Shinpei, envisioned a grand imperial capital that would project Japan's emerging power and prestige on the international stage, hoping to create a city that matched Paris and Berlin.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite the initial optimism, reconstruction planning was fraught with political contestation.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Gotō Shinpei, as Home Minister and head of the Reconstruction Institute (*Teito fukkōin*), championed ambitious and expensive plans, initially proposing a budget of ¥3 billion—more than twice the entire national budget at the time.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This was met with immediate opposition from Finance Minister Inoue Junnosuke and other cabinet colleagues, who were concerned about the nation's financial stability and favored a more fiscally conservative approach.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Debates raged over the scope of reconstruction, the extent of land readjustment, the design of new infrastructure, and, crucially, the budget.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Imperial Capital Reconstruction Deliberative Council (*Teito fukkō shingikai*), an advisory body of elder statesmen and party leaders, became the site of fierce opposition.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Critics, led by Itō Miyoji, argued the plans were extravagant, could lead to financial collapse, and violated constitutional rights to ownership.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The political infighting exposed deep divisions within Japan's elite and the structural weaknesses of its quasi-democratic, bureaucratic-oligarchic political system.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Gotō's plans were progressively scaled back, with the budget reduced to ¥597 million by the council and further to ¥468 million by the Diet in December 1923.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A key component of the physical reconstruction was land readjustment (*kukaku seiri*).
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Special Urban Planning Law of December 1923 empowered the government to rationalize irregular land plots, widen streets, and create public spaces by confiscating up to 10 percent of private land without monetary compensation.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly 30,000,000 square meters (320,000,000 sq ft) of land in Tokyo were divided into 66 readjustment districts.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While the process aimed to create a more rational and user-friendly urban environment, it was met with confusion, resistance, and numerous petitions from landowners and tenants.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Concerns involved the constitutionality of uncompensated land confiscation, the impact on businesses, the rights of tenants, and the adequacy of compensation for relocated structures.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite these local-level disputes, the program resulted in the rationalization of many neighborhoods, particularly in eastern Tokyo, and the creation of significant new public land for roads and other infrastructure.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Overall, about 15.3 percent of residential land in readjustment areas was converted to public use, with landowners compensated for acquisitions beyond the 10 percent threshold.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By the time reconstruction was officially celebrated in March 1930, Tokyo had undergone significant physical changes.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most notable successes were in transportation infrastructure.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The total area of roads in Tokyo increased by 45 percent, and many were widened and paved, with modern sidewalks.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Key arterial roads like Shōwa-dōri and Yasukuni-dōri were constructed, and new, modern steel bridges, such as the Eitai-bashi and Kiyosu-bashi spanning the Sumida River, became icons of the new city.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The river and canal system was also improved.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, many of the more ambitious social and environmental goals were not fully realized.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Spending on parks and green spaces, while resulting in three new large parks and 52 smaller ones, was limited.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Social welfare facilities, while improved, also received a small fraction of the reconstruction budget.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many of the pre-earthquake urban vulnerabilities and social problems, including slum areas, persisted or re-emerged.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The final reconstruction expenditure by national and city governments totaled roughly ¥744 million.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The site of the Honjo Clothing Depot, where tens of thousands perished, became a focal point for mourning and remembrance.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Plans for a memorial were initiated soon after the disaster.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In June 1924, the Taishō Earthquake Disaster Memorial Project Association was formed to oversee the project.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A national design competition for the memorial complex was launched in December 1924.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The winning entry by engineer-architect Maeda Kenjirō, a 53-meter (174 ft) tower, proved controversial due to its perceived resemblance to a Prussian triumphal tower and its perceived insensitivity to Buddhist sensibilities.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] After sustained protest, particularly from Buddhist federations, the design was scrapped in December 1926.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Engineer Itō Chūta was then appointed to create a new, more "Japanese" design, heavily influenced by Buddhist architecture, featuring a pagoda that would house a charnel house.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Earthquake Memorial Hall (later the Tokyo Metropolitan Memorial Hall) in Yokoamichō Park was completed on 1 September 1930.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake left an indelible mark on Japan.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] 1 September was designated as Disaster Prevention Day (防災の日, *Bōsai no hi*) in 1960, an annual commemoration involving nationwide disaster drills and awareness campaigns.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster highlighted urban vulnerabilities and influenced subsequent approaches to city planning and building codes, although the ideal of a truly disaster-proof city remained elusive.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The memory of the earthquake, particularly the firestorms and the Honjo Clothing Depot tragedy, continued to haunt Tokyoites, influencing their behavior even during the World War II bombings.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The events of 1923 also served as a catalyst for long-term government efforts to foster neighborhood associations (*tonarigumi*) and promote civil defense, trends that intensified in the 1930s and during the war.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disorientation and destruction caused by the disaster marked a "significant divide" in the "massification" of culture, consumption, and taste, accelerating social and cultural changes and providing a "free field" for new artistic and radical movements.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The center of urban life in Tokyo also shifted, as the old merchant quarters of the *shitamachi* ("Low City") were particularly devastated, pushing development toward the more residential "High City" (*yamanote*).
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite the significant scaling-back of Gotō Shinpei's original vision, the reconstruction provided a fine example of creative recovery, rebuilding Tokyo as a modern city and serving as a model for urban development throughout Japan until the end of World War II.
[src:edward-s-morse/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake and its aftermath remain a subject of historical study and public memory, serving as a stark reminder of Japan's seismic activity and the complex interplay of disaster, society, and national identity.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The **25th Maine Infantry Regiment** was an infantry regiment that served in the Union Army during the American Civil War.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 25th Maine Infantry was organized in Portland, Maine and mustered on September 29, 1862, for nine months' service under the command of Colonel Francis Fessenden.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment left Maine for Washington, D.C., October 16.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Attached to Casey's Division, Defenses of Washington, to February 1863.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] 1st Brigade, Casey's Division, XXII Corps, to April 1863.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] 1st Brigade, Abercrombie's Division, XXII Corps, to July 1863.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Served garrison duty in the defenses of Washington, D.C., October 18, 1862, to March 24, 1863.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Moved to Chantilly, Virginia, March 24, and on picket duty there until June 26.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] (Temporarily attached to XII Corps, Army of the Potomac.) Moved to Arlington Heights June 26, then ordered home June 30.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 25th Maine Infantry mustered out of service July 10, 1863.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Some of its members later joined the 30th Maine Volunteer Infantry Regiment.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment lost a total of 20 enlisted men during service, all due to disease.
[src:edward-s-morse/25th-maine-volunteer-infantry-regiment] 28, 1862 buried at Pine Grove Cemetery in Brunswick, ME (same cemetery as Joshua Chamberlain).
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:edward-s-morse/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:edward-s-morse/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse was born in Portland, Maine to Jonathan Kimball Morse and Jane Seymour (Becket) Morse.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] His father was a Congregationalist deacon who held strict Calvinist beliefs.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] His mother, who did not share her husband's religious beliefs, encouraged her son's interest in the sciences.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] An unruly student, Morse was expelled from all but one of the schools he attended in his youth — the Portland village school, the academy at Conway, New Hampshire, in 1851, and Bridgton Academy in 1854 (for carving on desks).
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He also attended Gould Academy in Bethel, Maine.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] At Gould Academy, Morse came under the influence of Dr.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Nathaniel True who encouraged Morse to pursue his interest in the study of nature.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He preferred to explore the Atlantic coast in search of shells and snails, or go to the field to study the fauna and flora.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] By the age of thirteen he had put together an impressive collection of shells.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Despite his lack of formal education, his collections soon earned him the visit of eminent scientists from Boston, Washington and even the United Kingdom.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He was noted for his work with land snails, and discovered two new species: *Helix asteriscus*, now known as *Planogyra asteriscus*, and *H.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Milium*, now known as *Striatura milium*.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] These species were presented at meetings of the Boston Society of Natural History in 1857 and 1859.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He was a gifted draftsman, a skill that served him well throughout his career.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] As a young man, it enabled him to be employed as a mechanical draftsman at the Portland Locomotive Company and later preparing wood engravings for natural history publications.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] This relatively well-paid work enabled him to save enough money to support his further education.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse was recommended by Philip Pearsall Carpenter to Louis Agassiz (1807–1873) at the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard University for his intellectual qualities and talent at drawing.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] After completing his studies he served as Agassiz's assistant in charge of conservation, documentation and drawing collections of mollusks and brachiopods until 1862.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He became especially interested in brachiopods during this time, and his first paper on the topic was published in 1862.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] During the American Civil War, Morse attempted to enlist in the 25th Maine Infantry, but was turned down due to a chronic tonsil infection.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] On June 18, 1863, Morse married Ellen ("Nellie") Elizabeth Owen in Portland.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] The couple had two children, Edith Owen Morse and John Gould Morse (named after Morse's lifelong friend Major John Mead Gould).
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse rapidly became successful in the field of zoology, specializing in malacology or the study of molluscs.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1864, he published his first work devoted to molluscs under the title *Observations On The Terrestrial Pulmonifera of Maine*.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse had been elected to the position of curator of the Portland Natural History Society, a position he hoped would become permanent, but in 1866 the Great Fire destroyed the buildings of the Society, along with much of Portland, and also the chance of a salaried position.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] An alternative opportunity arose with the foundation of the Peabody Academy of Science in Salem.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse returned to Massachusetts to work at the academy, along with Caleb Cooke, Alpheus Hyatt, Alpheus Spring Packard and Frederic Ward Putnam (director), all former students of Agassiz.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1867, along with Putnam, Hyatt and Packard, Morse co-founded the scientific journal *The American Naturalist*, and Morse became one of its editors.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] The establishment of the Journal was very important for American Natural History.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] It was written by experts in the field, but aimed to be accessible to a wide readership.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] This aim was greatly helped by the high quality of the illustrations, many of them provided by Morse himself.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse's desire to bring natural history to a wider audience also led him to give lectures to a variety of audiences.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] His combination of broad knowledge, speaking skill, and ability to draw quickly on the blackboard with both hands made him a popular presenter.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse continued his work on brachiopods, often considered to be his most important scientific work.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1869, he was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Between 1869 and 1873 he published a series of papers on the embryology and classification of the group.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Whereas in 1865 he had accepted the majority view that placed brachiopoda within the molluscs, in 1870 largely on the basis of embryological observations, he proposed that the brachiopoda should be removed from the molluscs, and placed within the annelids, a group of segmented worms.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Modern taxonomy agrees with the first of these propositions, but not the second, classifying molluscs, brachiopods and annelids as three separate phyla within the superphylum Lophotrochozoa.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Helen Muir-Wood has given an account of the history of the classification of the brachiopods that places Morse's work in its historical context.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] From 1871 to 1874, Morse was appointed to the chair of comparative anatomy and zoology at Bowdoin College.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1873 and 1874 he was a teacher at the summer school established by Agassiz on Penikese Island.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Though the school only operated for a few years, several of its students went on to distinguished careers, including David Starr Jordan.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1874, he became a lecturer at Harvard University.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1876, Morse was named a fellow of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1877, he provided the illustrations for a book by his friend John Mead Gould, entitled *How to camp out*.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] During this period the issue of evolution caused much discussion and controversy.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He argued that the persistence of animals such as *Lingula* (a brachiopod) over immense periods of time, from the Silurian to the present day, with little change was "a fatal objection to the theory of gradual development".
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] However all of his students subsequently adopted evolutionary theory in various forms.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He addresses the issue of human origins, and finds the evidence for "the lowly origin of man", and common ancestry with apes, convincing.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He did not only express these views in a western context, but was subsequently the first to bring Darwin's theory of evolution to Japan.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In June 1877 Morse first visited Japan in search of coastal brachiopods.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] His visit turned into a three-year stay when he was offered a post as the first professor of zoology at the Tokyo Imperial University.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He went on to recommend several fellow Americans as *o-yatoi gaikokujin* (foreign advisors) to support the modernization of Japan in the Meiji Era.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] To collect specimens, he established a marine biological laboratory at Enoshima in Kanagawa Prefecture.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] While looking out of a window on a train between Yokohama and Tokyo, Morse discovered the Ōmori shell mound, the excavation of which opened the study in archaeology and anthropology in Japan and shed much light on the material culture of prehistoric Japan.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He returned to Japan in 1882–3 to present a report of his findings to Tokyo Imperial University.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse had much interest in Japanese ceramics, making a collection of over 5,000 pieces of Japanese pottery.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] On his 1882-3 visit to Japan he collected clay samples as well as finished ceramics.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He devised the term "cord-marked" for the sherds of Stone Age pottery, decorated by impressing cords into the wet clay.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] The Japanese translation, "Jōmon," now gives its name to the whole Jōmon period as well as Jōmon pottery.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He brought back to Boston a collection amassed by government minister and amateur art collector Ōkuma Shigenobu, who donated it to Morse in recognition of his services to Japan.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] These now form part of the "Morse Collection" of the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] The catalogue is a monumental work, and still the only major work of its kind in English.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] His collection of daily artifacts of the Japanese people is kept at the Peabody Essex Museum in Salem, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] The remainder of the collection was inherited by his granddaughter, Catharine Robb Whyte via her mother Edith Morse Robb and is housed at the Whyte Museum of the Canadian Rockies, Banff, Alberta, Canada.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He travelled several times to the Far East which inspired several books, with his own illustrations.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] *Japanese Homes and Their Surroundings* was published in 1885; *On the Older Forms of Terra-cotta Roofing Tiles* in 1892; *Latrines of the East* in 1893; *Glimpses of China and Chinese Homes* in 1903; and *Japan Day by Day* in 1917.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] After leaving Japan, Morse traveled to Southeast Asia and Europe.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In subsequent years, he returned to Europe, and Japan in quest of pottery.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1886 Morse became president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He became Keeper of Pottery at the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston in 1890.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He was also a director of the Peabody Academy of Science (now part of and succeeded by the Peabody Essex Museum) in Salem from 1880 to 1914.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1898, he was awarded the Order of the Rising Sun (3rd class) by the Japanese government.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society in 1898.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He became chairman of the Boston Museum in 1914, and chairman of the Peabody Museum in 1915.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He was awarded the Order of the Sacred Treasures (2nd class) by the Japanese government in 1922.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse was a friend of astronomer Percival Lowell, who inspired interest in the planet Mars.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse would occasionally journey to the Lowell Observatory in Flagstaff, Arizona, during optimal viewing times to observe the planet.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1906, Morse published *Mars and Its Mystery* in defense of Lowell's controversial speculations regarding the possibility of life on Mars.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He donated over 10,000 books from his personal collection to the Tokyo Imperial University.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] On learning that the library of the Tokyo Imperial University was reduced to ashes by the 1923 Great Kantō earthquake, in his will he ordered that his entire remaining collection of books be donated to Tokyo Imperial University.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse's last paper, on shell-mounds, was published in 1925.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He died at his home in Salem, Massachusetts in December of that year, of cerebral hemorrhage.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] He was buried at the Harmony Grove Cemetery.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] In 1872, Morse noticed that mammals and reptiles with reduced fingers lose them from the sides in a particular order, beginning with the thumb and then the little finger.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Later researchers revealed that this is a general pattern in tetrapods (except Theropoda and Urodela): digits are reduced in the order I → V → II → III → IV, the reverse order of their appearance in embryogenesis.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] Morse has patented a solar air heater for domestic use, consisting of a glass box containing a black corrugated steel surface to capture solar heat.
[src:edward-s-morse/edward-s-morse] The device would be attached to external wall of the building and provide flow of warmed air.
